social_media={
    2001: "Ryze\nRyze is a social networking platform that was founded in 2001 by Adrian Scott. It was one of the first social networking sites aimed at business professionals, and it allowed users to create a profile, connect with other professionals in their industry, and join or create interest-based groups. Ryze gained popularity in the early 2000s and was acquired by the social media marketing company, HigherOne, in 2008.",
    2002: "Friendster\nFriendster was one of the earliest social media platforms,Friendster allowed users to create profiles, connect with friends, and join groups. It was popular in Asia, but eventually lost ground to Facebook and other competitors and was shut down in 2015.\n\nLinkedIn\nLinkedIn is a professional networking platform that helps users connect with other professionals, showcase their skills and experience, and search for job opportunities. Users create a personal profile that includes their work experience, education, skills, and other professional information. The platform has over 700 million users worldwide and is a valuable tool for job seekers, employers, and building professional connections.",
    2003: "MySpace\nMySpace was a social networking site that allowed users to create profiles, customize their pages with music and videos, and connect with friends. It was especially popular among musicians and artists, but lost ground to Facebook and other platforms in the late 2000s and early 2010s.",
    2004: 'Facebook\nFacebook is launched by Mark Zuckerberg and his college roommates. Initially only available to college students, it quickly expands to other universities and eventually becomes available to the general public.',
    2005: 'Youtube\nYouTube, a video sharing platform, is launched. It quickly becomes one of the most popular websites on the internet, with users uploading and watching billions of videos each day.\n\nBebo\nBebo is a social networking website that was founded in 2005 and is based in San Francisco, California. The platform was popular in the mid-2000s, particularly among young people, before declining in popularity and eventually shutting down in 2013. In 2019, Bebo was relaunched as a streaming service that allows users to watch movies and TV shows for free, supported by advertising. ',
    2006: 'Twitter\nTwitter, a microblogging platform, is launched. It allows users to post short messages, or "tweets," which are limited to 280 characters. Twitter quickly becomes a popular platform for news and political commentary.',
    2007: 'Tumblr\nTumblr, a blogging and social media platform, is launched. It allows users to create blogs and share multimedia content, such as photos, videos, and GIFs.',
    2008: 'Spotify\nSpotify is a music streaming platform that was founded in Sweden in 2006 by Daniel Ek and Martin Lorentzon. It allows users to stream music and podcasts from a library of millions of songs, both from major record labels and independent artists. The platform is available in over 70 countries and has over 320 million active users as of February 2021.',
    2009: 'Quora\nQuora is a question-and-answer website that allows users to ask, answer, and explore a wide range of topics. The platform was founded in 2009 and is headquartered in Mountain View, California. Users can ask questions on any topic, and other users can provide answers, comments, and upvotes. Quora also features a feed of questions and answers tailored to each user\'s interests and activity on the platform. ',
    2010: 'Instagram\nInstagram, a photo and video sharing platform, is launched. It quickly becomes popular among young people and is eventually acquired by Facebook in 2012.',
    2011: 'Snapchat\nSnapchat, a messaging and multimedia sharing platform, is launched. It allows users to send photos and videos that disappear after a short time, and quickly becomes popular among younger users.\n\nWeChat\nWeChat is a Chinese multi-purpose messaging, social media, and mobile payment app developed by Tencent. The app was first released in 2011 and is one of the largest social media platforms in China, with over one billion monthly active users. WeChat allows users to send text and voice messages, make voice and video calls, share photos and videos, post on a timeline, and follow official accounts of businesses, celebrities, and media outlets.\n\nNextDoor\nNextdoor is a social networking platform designed for local communities. The platform was launched in 2011 and is headquartered in San Francisco, California. Nextdoor allows users to connect with neighbors and local businesses to share information, ask for recommendations, and discuss local issues. Users must verify their address to join a neighborhood group, ensuring that the platform is limited to residents of a specific area.',
    2012: 'Pinterest\nPinterest, a social media platform for sharing and organizing images, is launched. It allows users to create "boards" and pin images to them, making it popular among people looking for inspiration for fashion, home decor, and other areas.',
    2013: 'Vine\nVine was a social media platform that allowed users to create and share 6-second looping videos. It was launched in January 2013 and quickly gained popularity among younger users, who enjoyed creating and sharing short, often humorous videos. Vine was unique in that it required users to create content within the constraints of a short time limit, which challenged users to be creative and innovative.',
    2014: 'Ello\nEllo is a social media platform that aims to provide an ad-free and non-commercial alternative to traditional social networks. The platform was launched in 2014 and is based in Burlington, Vermont. Ello\'s key features include a minimalist design, no advertising, and a focus on creative and visual content. Users can follow other users and engage with their posts through comments and likes. Ello is popular among artists, designers, and other creatives looking for a platform to showcase their work without the distractions of advertising and algorithmic feeds.',
    2015: 'Periscope\nPeriscope, a live video streaming platform, is launched in 2015. It allows users to broadcast live video to their followers, and quickly becomes popular among journalists and content creators.\n\nDiscord\nDiscord is a voice, video, and text communication platform designed for gamers, but has since expanded to include communities of all kinds. The platform was launched in 2015 and is based in San Francisco, California. Discord allows users to create and join servers, which are essentially virtual spaces where users can communicate via text, voice, and video channels. Users can also share files, images, and other media through the platform. ',
    2016: 'Tiktok\nTikTok, a short-form video sharing platform, is launched. It allows users to create short videos set to music, and becomes hugely popular among younger users.',
    2017: 'Sarahah\nSarahah was launched in June 2017 and quickly gained popularity among teenagers and young adults, particularly on Snapchat, where users would share links to their Sarahah profiles and ask for anonymous feedback from their friends. However, the platform was criticized for facilitating cyberbullying and harassment, as users could send hurtful or abusive messages without fear of consequences.',
    2018: 'Lasso\nLasso was a short-form video app launched by Facebook in November 2018. It was similar to the popular app TikTok, allowing users to create and share 15-second videos set to music and filters.Lasso was aimed at younger audiences and was designed to compete with TikTok, which was rapidly growing in popularity at the time. However, Lasso struggled to gain traction and was eventually shut down in July 2020, less than two years after its initial launch.',
    2019: 'Rizzle\nRizzle is a short-form video app that allows users to create and share 60-second videos on a wide range of topics. The platform was launched in 2019 and is based in San Francisco, California. Rizzle is designed to promote creativity and authentic content by allowing users to create series of short videos on a specific theme or topic. Users can collaborate with others to create split-screen videos and can follow other users to discover new content.',
    2020: 'Clubhouse\nClubhouse is an invite-only audio-based social media platform that allows users to join virtual rooms to have live conversations with others. The platform was launched in 2020 and is based in San Francisco, California. Users can participate in conversations by speaking or listening, and can create or join rooms on a wide range of topics, from business and technology to entertainment and social issues. ',
}
